Ah, no. The difference is that 2000 years from now people will be able to pull from multiple sources with multiple biases and gather information about what happened to WTC, the people and the USA. That can't be said about the Bible. I shouldn't have to point out that 1) there are no original &quot;scriptures&quot; that can be examined. 2) What fragments are available to scholars have been &quot;modified&quot; by scribes through that ages. 3) The writters of the texts that compose the canons for Old Testament and New Testament of the Christian bible are relatively unknown. For example, we don't *know* who actually wrote the Gospel of &quot;Luke&quot;. 4) The current christian canon was voted upon by the Council of Nicea in the 4th century AD. Sure took a long time for christians to figure out what the &quot;word of God&quot; was! =) 5) There are no other historical texts outside of the New Testament that can collaborate what the Gospels say about a man named Jesus. Some here have quoted Josephus, but if they did their home work they would know that the quotes they offer are considered spurious by most New Testamanent scholars today (perhaps those who offer Josephus should stop reading Josh McDowell and counting a columnist as a scholar!).<br>
<br>
Finally, the idea that the &quot;Word of God&quot; (Old and New Testaments of the Bible) is inerrant is laughable at best and only the most fundamental even consider such a doctrine.<br>
